04621nam a22006375i 9780748634484DE-B159720220306030904.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220306t20222009stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486344847 a10.1515/97807486344842doi  a(DE-B1597)614166  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aPER0040302bisacsh1 aMcNair, Brian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJournalists in Film :bHeroes and Villains /cBrian McNair. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b1 B/W tables 30 B/W halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tPreface and acknowledgements -- tPart I Introductions and Overviews -- t1 Introduction -- t2 A good tradition of love and hate -- t3 Heroes and villains – an overview of journalism on film -- t4 Journalism in Film: 1997–2008 -- tPart II Heroes -- t5 Watchdogs -- t6 Witnesses -- t7 Heroines -- t8 Artists -- tPart III Villains -- t9 Rogues, reptiles and repentant sinners -- t10 Fabricators, fakers, fraudsters -- t11 King-makers -- t12 In closing -- tAppendix Films about journalism, 1997–2008 -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGBS_insertPreviewButtonPopup('ISBN:9780748634477);We both love and hate our journalists. They are perceived as sexy and glamorous on the one hand, despicable and sleazy on the other. Opinion polls regularly indicate that we experience a kind of cultural schizophrenia in our relationship to journalists and the news media: sometimes they are viewed as heroes, at other times villains. From Watergate to the fabrication scandals of the 2000s, journalists have risen and fallen in public esteem.In this book, leading journalism studies scholar Brian McNair explores how journalists have been represented through the prism of one of our key cultural forms, cinema. Drawing on the history of cinema since the 1930s, and with a focus on the period 1997-2008, McNair explores how journalists have been portrayed in film, and what these images tell us about the role of the journalist in liberal democratic societies. Separate chapters are devoted to the subject of female journalists in film, foreign correspondents, investigative reporters and other categories of news maker who have featured regularly in cinema. The book also discusses the representation of public relations professionals in film.Illustrated throughout and written in an accessible and lively style suitable for academic and lay readers alike, Journalists in Film will be essential reading for students and teachers of journalism, and for all those concerned about the role of the journalist in contemporary society, not least journalists themselves. An appendix contains mini-essays on every film about journalism released in the cinema between 1997 and 2008."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aJournalists in motion pictures. 0aMotion picturesxHistory. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780748634484zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748634484423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748634484/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK